				<title><![CDATA[Top 8 Exercises For A Full Body Bodyweight Workout According To A Personal Trainer]]></title>
				<link>https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/full-body-bodyweight-workout</link>
				<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.endomondo.com/?post_type=informational_posts&#038;p=33781</guid>
				<pubDate>Tue, 14 Jan 2025 02:36:42 +0000				</pubDate>
				<dc:creator><![CDATA[Jessica Forster]]></dc:creator>
						<category><![CDATA[Exercise]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Best Exercises]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Calisthenics]]></category>
				<description>
					<![CDATA[
				Discover the best full body bodyweight workout in %%currentyear%% for strength and endurance. Achieve balanced results with zero equipment.				]]>
				</description>
				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
											<figure>
															<img src="https://www.endomondo.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/full-body-bodyweight-workout-endomondo.jpg" alt="">
															<figcaption>A full body bodyweight workout is an efficient and effective way to build greater strength, endurance, and mobility. <span>Photo: Freepik</span></figcaption>
													</figure>
					<p>You don’t have access to a gym? That’s not a problem. A full body bodyweight workout can build strength, boost endurance, and enhance mobility anytime, anywhere.</p><p><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/body-weight-exercises" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Bodyweight exercises</a> challenge your muscles using nothing but gravity and your body. They’re simple, effective, and perfect for every fitness level. Whether you’re new to exercise or looking for a fresh routine, bodyweight training fits into any lifestyle.</p><p>In this article, we’ll guide you through a range of exercises to target all major muscle groups in one workout. If you’re ready to transform your fitness and feel stronger in daily life, this workout is for you. Let’s explore the best bodyweight exercises for a stronger, healthier you.</p><div class="wp-block-group ft-snippet"><p class="has-medium-font-size">8 Moves For A Full Body Bodyweight Workout</p><p>This full body bodyweight workout builds strength, endurance, and functional fitness by targeting all major muscle groups. Incorporate them into your routine for a complete and effective workout:</p><ul><li><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/#Push-Up">Push-Up.</a></li><li><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/#Dip">Dip.</a></li><li><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/#Plank">Plank.</a></li><li><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/#Pull-Up">Pull-Up.</a></li><li><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/#Squat">Squat.</a></li><li><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/#Bodyweight-Single-Leg-Deadlift">Bodyweight Single-Leg Deadlift.</a></li><li><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/#Mountain-Climber">Mountain Climber.</a></li><li><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/#Burpee">Burpee.</a></li></ul></div></div><h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dip">Dip</h3><p><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/chest-dip" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Dips</a> are a compound bodyweight exercise that effectively targets the chest and <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30725681/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">triceps</a>. They also engage the shoulders, core, and stabilizers, making them excellent for upper body strength and stability.&nbsp;</p><p>This exercise is versatile, as you can perform them on parallel bars, dip stations, or even sturdy furniture. Furthermore, there are many available variations of the exercise and options to change the grip. This allows you to <a href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/331477905_A_COMPARATIVE_ELECTROMYOGRAPHICAL_INVESTIGATION_OF_TRICEPS_BRACHII_AND_PECTORALIS_MAJOR_DURING_FOUR_DIFFERENT_FREEHAND_EXERCISES" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">vary muscle focus and adjust intensity</a> to suit your fitness level.</p><p>They are ideal for building pushing strength and improving muscle definition.</p></div><h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Plank">Plank</h3><p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/plank-guide" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">plank</a> is an isometric bodyweight exercise, which means it engages the muscles without moving or changing their length. This exercise engages the <a href="https://europepmc.org/article/NBK/nbk551649" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">core muscles</a> to hold the position.&nbsp;</p><p>The core stabilization of this exercise enhances muscular endurance and helps <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34487008/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">reduce lower back pain</a>. It also engages the shoulders, chest, back, and glutes, making it a highly effective full-body stability exercise.&nbsp;</p></div><h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Pull-Up">Pull-Up</h3><p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/pull-up" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">pull-up</a> is a powerful bodyweight exercise that intensely works the back muscles. During a traditional pull-up, the <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28846224/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">lats</a> can work at about <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5548150/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">80% of their maximum capacity</a>. Thus, making it ideal for sculpting a more defined muscular back.</p><p>It also engages the <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30137823/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">biceps</a>, shoulders, and core, making it a staple in any <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/upper-body-bodyweight-workout" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">upper body bodyweight workout</a>. The exercise requires a pull-up bar or similar sturdy surface and can be modified for beginners or advanced athletes.</p></div><h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Squat">Squat</h3><p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/bodyweight-squat" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">squat</a> is a foundational lower-body exercise that primarily targets the <a href="https://europepmc.org/article/nbk/nbk513334" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">quadriceps</a> while also engaging the glutes, hamstrings, and core. This functional movement mimics everyday actions like sitting and standing, improving strength, balance, and mobility.&nbsp;</p><p>Squats are highly versatile and can be modified to suit the user. For example, <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34717162/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">stance width and toe direction</a> can be altered to change muscle focus and joint pressure.&nbsp;</p></div><h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Bodyweight-Single-Leg-Deadlift">Bodyweight Single-Leg Deadlift</h3><p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/bodyweight-single-leg-deadlift" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">bodyweight single-leg deadlift</a> is a unilateral (one-sided) exercise that effectively works the <a href="https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/physiology/articles/10.3389/fphys.2021.694604/full" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">hamstrings</a> and <a href="https://europepmc.org/article/nbk/nbk538193" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">glutes</a>. It also engages your core and improves balance, coordination, and stability.&nbsp;</p><p>This movement is ideal for enhancing lower-body strength while addressing <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36035582/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">muscular imbalances</a>. This is because training one side at a time ensures that a stronger side doesn’t compensate for the weaker side.&nbsp;</p></div><h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Mountain-Climber">Mountain Climber</h3><p><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/mountain-climber" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Mountain climbers</a> are a dynamic exercise that heavily engages the abdominal muscles. In addition, the shoulders, chest, and legs are activated throughout.&nbsp;</p><p>Mountain climbers and other high-intensity calisthenics also <a href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/357186499_Repetitive_sprint_or_calisthenics_training_which_is_more_successful_for_athletic_performance" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">improve aerobic endurance and body composition</a>. This is due to the effective combination of strength-based training with fast-paced movements.&nbsp;</p></div><h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Burpee">Burpee</h3><p>The burpee is an energetic full-body exercise that targets multiple muscle groups, including the chest, legs, core, and shoulders.&nbsp;</p><p>High-intensity full-body training elevates your heart rate and <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34987590/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">strengthens your cardiovascular system</a>. Burpees combine strength and cardio, making them effective for building endurance, burning calories, and improving overall fitness.&nbsp;</p></div><h2 class="wp-block-heading">Best Full Body Bodyweight Routine</h2><p>This <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/workouts/bodyweight-workout-plan" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">bodyweight workout plan</a> is designed to target all major muscle groups, building strength, endurance, and balance. The <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7927075/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">routine</a> combines dynamic and static movements to challenge your muscles and improve functional fitness. Perform this workout 2–3 times per week, allowing <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00421-017-3725-7" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">48–72 hours</a> in between for proper recovery. Remember to include a <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s40279-017-0797-9" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">dynamic warm-up</a> before starting to <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33188962/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">reduce injury risk</a> and finish with a cooldown to aid recovery.</p><h2 class="wp-block-heading list-start">Benefits Of A Full Body Bodyweight Workout</h2><h3 class="wp-block-heading">Balanced And Efficient</h3><p>Full body bodyweight workouts promote balanced development by targeting multiple muscle groups in one session. Combining exercises such as pull-ups, push-ups, and squats ensures you are training all parts of your body.&nbsp;</p><p>With busy schedules, finding time to work out every day can feel impossible for a lot of people. Full-body workouts solve this by maximizing efficiency, allowing you to effectively train your entire body using limited time.</p><p>Furthermore, this comprehensive approach trains your entire body evenly, helping prevent <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36035582/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">muscular imbalances</a>. It prevents overtraining specific areas while neglecting others.</p><h3 class="wp-block-heading">Accessible And Adaptable</h3><figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img src="https://www.endomondo.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Accessible-And-Adaptable-endomondo.jpg" alt="Accessible And Adaptable" class="wp-image-33839"/>Bodyweight exercises can be performed at home, outdoors, or while traveling. <span>Photo: nomadsoul1/Freepik</span></figure><p>Bodyweight workouts are accessible and adaptable, <a href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/317321468_The_effects_of_a_calisthenics_training_intervention_on_posture_strength_and_body_composition" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">improving posture, strength, and body composition</a> without requiring major training equipment and space. You can perform them at home, outdoors, or while traveling. This can increase the likelihood of consistency for many people, which is the key to results.</p><p>Furthermore, bodyweight exercises are suitable for people with varying fitness levels, from beginners to advanced athletes. Exercises can be modified easily to increase or decrease intensity, aligning with your goals and capabilities.&nbsp;</p><p>Resistance bands or support props can lessen the load your body needs to lift or hold, making exercises more beginner-friendly. On the other hand, more reps, longer hold, and added weight can increase the challenge for the more experienced.</p><p>Whether focusing on strength, <a href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/379754047_The_Effect_of_10-week_Whole-body_Calisthenics_Training_Program_on_the_Muscular_Endurance_of_Untrained_Collegiate_Students" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">muscular endurance</a>, or functional movement, bodyweight routines provide endless possibilities.</p><h3 class="wp-block-heading">Improves Daily Life</h3><p>Daily life can be improved with bodyweight workouts by building strength, stability, and mobility that carry over into everyday tasks.</p><p>An essential part of bodyweight exercises is core engagement as it stabilizes the body throughout movements. Improved core strength supports enhanced posture and <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34847915/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">better balance, and reduces back pain</a> in day-to-day life.&nbsp;</p><p>Furthermore, many functional movements in bodyweight exercises mimic real-life actions. For example, step-ups mirror climbing stairs and squats use the same muscles as sitting down and standing up. Thus, meaning as you get stronger in the exercise, the more those muscles can support you in real-life situations.&nbsp;</p><p>Moreover, <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28473283/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">daily life</a> requires your joints to be mobile and they are constantly working through different ranges of motion. Greater joint mobility allows you to move with ease, helping to prevent stiffness and discomfort during daily routine activities. Bodyweight exercises practice taking your joints through a full range of motion and strengthening <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507893/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">the muscles that support them</a>.</p><h2 class="wp-block-heading">Expert Training Tips&nbsp;</h2><ul><li>Perform exercises through a full range of motion. This activates more muscle fibers and <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2411-5142/9/1/9" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">maximizes hypertrophy</a> (muscle growth).</li><li>Use controlled, steady movements to avoid relying on momentum and ensure optimal muscle activation during each repetition.</li><li>Take short rest periods (<a href="https://www.mdpi.com/1660-4601/16/24/4897" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">approximately 60 seconds</a>) between exercises to maintain intensity while giving your muscles enough time to recover.</li><li>Balance your exercises for an effective full-body workout. For example, incorporating the upper body, lower body, and core, pushing and pulling, bilateral and unilateral, and static and dynamic.</li><li>Use <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27219125/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">progressive overload</a> to maximize muscle growth. Gradually increase reps, sets, or intensity to challenge your muscles and optimize strength and endurance gains.</li></ul><h2 class="wp-block-heading">Conclusion</h2><p>A full body bodyweight workout is an efficient and effective way to build greater strength, endurance, and mobility without equipment. By targeting all major muscles, these exercises ensure balanced development and functional fitness.</p><p>The versatility of bodyweight training allows you to work out anywhere, adapting movements to suit your fitness level. Embrace the challenge and enjoy the long-term benefits of full-body bodyweight training.</p><div class="wp-block-group"><h2 class="wp-block-heading faq-heading">Frequently Asked Questions</h2><div class="schema-faq wp-block-yoast-faq-block"><div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1623393125914"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Is it OK to always do full-body workouts?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Yes, it’s fine to focus on full-body workouts if balanced. Allow proper rest between sessions to prevent overtraining and injuries. Full-body routines are ideal for building strength, improving endurance, and maintaining overall fitness when done consistently and mindfully.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1734331256791"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Is full body 3 times a week enough?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Yes, training with full-body workouts <a href="https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Ali-Erdem-Cigerci/publication/342339065_The_Effect_of_Calisthenics_Exercises_on_Body_Composition_in_Soccer_Players/links/5eee7aff299bf1faac68c131/The-Effect-of-Calisthenics-Exercises-on-Body-Composition-in-Soccer-Players.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">three times weekly</a> is effective and can increase lean body mass. It provides enough stimulus for strength gains while allowing sufficient muscle recovery.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1734331257345"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Can I get ripped with bodyweight exercises?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Yes, bodyweight exercises can build muscle and burn fat, helping you get ripped. Combine progressive overload, a calorie deficit, and consistency. These exercises can improve strength and definition when paired with a balanced, <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5401959/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">protein</a>-rich diet.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1734331257834"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Why is calisthenics better than the gym?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">A <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/full-body-calisthenics-workout" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">full body calisthenics workout</a> is more accessible than a gym workout because it requires no equipment or memberships. Its adaptability allows training anywhere, making it ideal for beginners and advanced athletes who value versatility and simplicity.</p> </div> </div></div>					]]>
